{
  "text": "Relative soil moisture content estimation from SAR images through the use of multi-temporal indexes for change detection may have better potential than an absolute estimation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . This approach is based on the assumption that the temporal variability of surface roughness and natural vegetation biomass is generally at a much longer time scale than that of soil moisture [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Thus, the change in SAR between repeat passes results from the change in soil moisture (with images acquired under similar satellite configuration and incidence angle). Two SAR indexes have been thus proposed, the Normalized Backscattering Soil Moisture Index (NBMI) [CITATION_5] and the Delta Index (∆-Index) [CITATION_6] . NBMI is derived from σ° measurements at two times (t 1 and t 2 ) over one location, where",
